WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:57.224 --> 00:00:58.290
[country music]

00:00:59.975 --> 00:01:01.181
[Peter] Nice ride Steve.

00:01:01.248 --> 00:01:04.153
-[Steve] Guy asked fifteen hundred bucks.
-Are you serious?

00:01:04.220 --> 00:01:06.553
I spent my bill money man.
I spent my…

00:01:06.620 --> 00:01:09.306
My phone, my cable, everything.

00:01:09.373 --> 00:01:11.926
Man I spent it and bought…
fifteen hundred bucks.

00:01:11.993 --> 00:01:15.683
-You're styling Steve.
-I was offered six grand the next day.

00:01:15.750 --> 00:01:17.562
Steve, thanks for meeting up, buddy.

00:01:17.629 --> 00:01:18.664
Oh, I love it.

00:01:18.731 --> 00:01:21.997
For those that watch the channel,
a month and a half ago?

00:01:22.064 --> 00:01:23.939
-Yeah something like that.
-We met up.

00:01:24.006 --> 00:01:26.803
You came in
at the end of the video randomly.

00:01:26.870 --> 00:01:29.745
I didn't want you to go
'cause I was in a hurry. Remember?

00:01:29.812 --> 00:01:32.139
Yeah. Had to come back
and get Steve's story.

00:01:32.206 --> 00:01:34.926
A lot of people asked, Steve,
because you grew up here.

00:01:34.993 --> 00:01:37.018
-I grew up here.
-You got the stories.

00:01:37.085 --> 00:01:38.913
And we're gonna start out there.

00:01:38.980 --> 00:01:42.513
One of your more interesting parts of life,
running drugs through the mangroves.

00:01:42.580 --> 00:01:44.018
-We're gonna show you.
-Okay.

00:01:44.085 --> 00:01:45.834
And then we'll get into your story,

00:01:45.901 --> 00:01:47.603
get into the deep dive local stuff.

00:01:47.670 --> 00:01:49.710
Family's been here since the 1850s.

00:01:50.265 --> 00:01:52.894
[Peter gasps] And you're saying
this is the last of these?

00:01:52.961 --> 00:01:54.514
This is the last of that.

00:01:54.581 --> 00:01:56.790
Aaron's a local. He owns the place.

00:01:56.857 --> 00:01:58.265
He's born and raised here.

00:01:58.599 --> 00:02:02.949
His grandfather
was the very first stone crabber.

00:02:03.606 --> 00:02:05.114
-Yeah.
-[Aaron] Ernest Hamilton.

00:02:05.181 --> 00:02:06.105
Ernest Hamilton.

00:02:06.631 --> 00:02:08.573
So he goes back a long ways.

00:02:08.640 --> 00:02:10.873
-Aaron's endangered species?
-Most certainly.

00:02:10.940 --> 00:02:15.133
Yeah. We had stone crab stuffing,
stone crab anything.

00:02:15.200 --> 00:02:18.302
Yeah. Where people like me
were eating deer meat and stuff

00:02:18.369 --> 00:02:20.548
his family was eating stone crabs.

00:02:20.615 --> 00:02:23.810
'Cause they didn't know
what to do with them to begin with.

00:02:24.916 --> 00:02:26.931
-Let me get in the rope.
-You don't need it.

00:02:26.998 --> 00:02:27.998
-Okay.
-I got you.

00:02:28.890 --> 00:02:30.050
[Peter] Oh that's cool.

00:02:30.117 --> 00:02:31.558
-Ain't it cool?
-Yeah.

00:02:31.625 --> 00:02:32.535
I love this.

00:02:32.602 --> 00:02:34.536
-One finger.
-It's old school.

00:02:34.603 --> 00:02:35.603
[winch whirrs]

00:02:36.635 --> 00:02:40.228
[Aaron] They built things
back in the good old days to have.

00:02:40.295 --> 00:02:43.592
Get a little grease on it, 
a little tender love and care it'll last…

00:02:43.659 --> 00:02:46.232
-[Steve] That's what she said.
-[laughter]

00:02:47.372 --> 00:02:48.392
Come on, man.

00:02:48.869 --> 00:02:50.437
All right. Thank you Aaron.

00:02:50.681 --> 00:02:53.214
[Steve] You can untie me.
Just turn that loose. Yeah.

00:02:53.281 --> 00:02:54.281
[country music]

00:02:59.333 --> 00:03:03.001
Hold on to your hat 'cause if it flies off
we ain't gonna go back and get it.

00:03:03.068 --> 00:03:03.984
All right.

00:03:04.051 --> 00:03:05.131
[music continues]

00:03:13.036 --> 00:03:16.770
Steve that's cool. Right at this area
you start to smell salt water.

00:03:16.837 --> 00:03:19.237
Because we're getting
further closer to the Gulf.

00:03:23.034 --> 00:03:27.505
Peter if you look way down there
and see the furthest island sticking out…

00:03:27.572 --> 00:03:29.651
-Yep.
-That's called Pavilion Key.

00:03:30.058 --> 00:03:33.168
Right on the end of it
there used to be a light right there.

00:03:33.590 --> 00:03:36.220
Usually we would meet right there

00:03:36.287 --> 00:03:39.027
and go out maybe a mile,
to three, four miles.

00:03:39.431 --> 00:03:41.191
We had 24-foot boats.

00:03:41.606 --> 00:03:44.662
That's what we ended up with
in the very end of the smuggling.

00:03:44.729 --> 00:03:47.463
That were 10-foot wide
had two motors on the back

00:03:47.530 --> 00:03:49.188
and a little console like this.

00:03:49.255 --> 00:03:52.223
The rest was open for throwing bales.

00:03:52.290 --> 00:03:54.323
Okay. What year are we talking Steve?

00:03:54.390 --> 00:03:56.590
For them style boats '81.

00:03:56.657 --> 00:03:59.380
-81.
So the drugs were coming from where? Cuba?

00:03:59.447 --> 00:04:00.507
No Colombia.

00:04:00.574 --> 00:04:04.830
The bosses which was my cousin,
he had friends in Miami

00:04:04.897 --> 00:04:07.801
that were Cubans
that were married to Colombians.

00:04:08.595 --> 00:04:11.443
-Oh.
-So the Colombians would set up deals.

00:04:11.510 --> 00:04:15.803
They would send shrimp boats over
to pick up 50,000 pounds.

00:04:15.870 --> 00:04:18.870
And then the shrimp boats
would come into the shore.

00:04:19.370 --> 00:04:22.901
And then we would go to the shrimp boats
pick it up in smaller boats

00:04:22.968 --> 00:04:24.443
and haul it inshore.

00:04:24.960 --> 00:04:28.606
Every now and then
you'd get a batch from Jamaica.

00:04:28.673 --> 00:04:30.714
And it was junk. Jamaican weed.

00:04:30.781 --> 00:04:32.863
All of it back then
compared to today was junk.

00:04:32.930 --> 00:04:34.124
-It was everything right?

00:04:34.191 --> 00:04:35.564
No just weed.

00:04:35.631 --> 00:04:36.956
-Just weed?
-Just weed.

00:04:37.023 --> 00:04:38.233
We didn't haul…

00:04:38.300 --> 00:04:43.668
Every now and then we would find a bale
that would have a red R or a number on it.

00:04:43.735 --> 00:04:46.326
We'd cut it open.
It would be full of Quaalude.

00:04:46.393 --> 00:04:47.538
Bags of Quaaludes .

00:04:47.605 --> 00:04:48.855
We dumped them overboard.

00:04:49.640 --> 00:04:53.256
Well you know getting caught
with marijuana you might get five years.

00:04:53.323 --> 00:04:56.953
You get caught with cocaine or Quaaludes

00:04:57.020 --> 00:04:58.359
that's another ten.

00:04:58.426 --> 00:05:00.993
Or guns. We never hauled guns. Never.

00:05:01.060 --> 00:05:04.392
The marijuana smuggling
run from late '70s

00:05:04.853 --> 00:05:08.439
up, us, our family, up into '85.

00:05:10.605 --> 00:05:14.364
[Peter] So you get your shipment
and then you just start blasting it in.

00:05:14.431 --> 00:05:16.331
We'd go through all these different…

00:05:16.871 --> 00:05:19.528
We had a watch out that would watch for us.

00:05:20.007 --> 00:05:21.213
And we would go in.

00:05:21.280 --> 00:05:23.079
It's according to where we was taking it.

00:05:23.146 --> 00:05:25.751
Everglades, Chokoloskee, to the road,

00:05:25.818 --> 00:05:27.786
whichever pass we would go in.

00:05:27.853 --> 00:05:29.830
And so were the feds chasing you here?

00:05:29.897 --> 00:05:33.762
Oh Lord, son, the feds,
the state, the feds, everybody.

00:05:34.329 --> 00:05:35.871
But you know what would happen?

00:05:35.938 --> 00:05:38.304
When they would get into here
they'd turn around.

00:05:38.752 --> 00:05:41.032
They didn't have GPS.
They couldn't follow us.

00:05:41.099 --> 00:05:43.334
Once we got into the island
we didn't worry

00:05:43.401 --> 00:05:46.028
'cause we all knew
that they couldn't find us.

00:05:46.095 --> 00:05:48.076
-They just didn't want to deal with this?

00:05:48.143 --> 00:05:49.103
They didn't know it.

00:05:49.170 --> 00:05:52.158
Did you see the oyster bars
running around everywhere?

00:05:52.225 --> 00:05:53.333
They didn't know it.

00:05:53.400 --> 00:05:56.060
-You just had to get the product this far.
-That's it.

00:05:56.127 --> 00:05:57.457
-And you're good?
-That's it.

00:05:57.524 --> 00:06:00.493
That's the backside
of where my family lived right here.

00:06:00.560 --> 00:06:04.529
Every bit of this island
was brought in by Calusa Indians.

00:06:04.596 --> 00:06:06.435
-Seriously?
-Seriously.

00:06:06.502 --> 00:06:11.339
Every oyster to shell that you pick up
was brought in by an Indian Calusa.

00:06:11.406 --> 00:06:14.392
My family,
when they moved from central Florida,

00:06:14.459 --> 00:06:16.864
this is where they come to in the 1850s.

00:06:16.931 --> 00:06:20.198
-1850s, your family's been here since?
-They moved to this island.

00:06:20.265 --> 00:06:22.008
Oh can we get out there?

00:06:22.075 --> 00:06:24.184
We sure can
but we're gonna go to the dock.

00:06:24.251 --> 00:06:26.127
Before we get into the island story

00:06:26.194 --> 00:06:28.422
how did the family
get into the drug business?

00:06:28.489 --> 00:06:30.826
We're fishermen, commercial fishermen.

00:06:30.893 --> 00:06:33.474
When the National Park
took over in '47

00:06:33.541 --> 00:06:36.972
they promised us
that they would never stop our fishing.

00:06:37.505 --> 00:06:39.173
-And they did.
-Okay.

00:06:39.240 --> 00:06:41.129
So we didn't have
no more way of living

00:06:41.196 --> 00:06:44.020
when they go
"You can't commercial fish no more."

00:06:44.840 --> 00:06:47.423
It ain't like we had
a million dollars saved up.

00:06:47.490 --> 00:06:50.683
So the marijuana smuggling,
some people were already doing it.

00:06:50.750 --> 00:06:53.832
So we just kind of joined in
and it got big.

00:06:55.132 --> 00:06:57.531
Our family was the largest

00:06:57.598 --> 00:06:59.828
about 30 of us, just family,

00:06:59.895 --> 00:07:04.073
was the largest
smuggling operation in South Florida.

00:07:04.140 --> 00:07:08.483
We brought in
millions of pounds of weed of marijuana.

00:07:08.550 --> 00:07:10.487
-Were you swimming in money back then?

00:07:10.554 --> 00:07:11.727
Just unbelievable.

00:07:11.794 --> 00:07:12.941
-Swimming?
-Swimming.

00:07:13.008 --> 00:07:15.451
-All you want.
-What were you doing with it?

00:07:15.524 --> 00:07:18.151
Giving it away buying stuff that…

00:07:18.218 --> 00:07:20.421
You understand,
we were poor all of our life.

00:07:20.488 --> 00:07:22.531
I never even had a three-Wheeler.

00:07:22.598 --> 00:07:25.540
I had three-wheelers,
and air boats, and trucks.

00:07:26.108 --> 00:07:28.070
I opened the door of my house one day

00:07:28.137 --> 00:07:31.396
and I looked down at my yard
at all the stuff I got and I'm going

00:07:32.304 --> 00:07:33.951
I wonder why I'm gonna jail.

00:07:34.365 --> 00:07:37.343
-And how old were you
at this time back in '81?

00:07:37.410 --> 00:07:39.463
Twenty-something. Early 20s.

00:07:39.530 --> 00:07:44.048
-And so you're doing weed so it's not
hardcore pills, it's not heroin.

00:07:44.115 --> 00:07:47.126
Pete, nowadays,
if they was to catch us with that weed

00:07:47.193 --> 00:07:49.618
they'd give us a pack of rolling papers.

00:07:49.685 --> 00:07:52.086
You know what I mean?
It don't mean nothing now.

00:07:52.153 --> 00:07:56.546
But you got to think around every point
there's oyster bars coming off.

00:07:57.060 --> 00:08:00.178
And if you try to catch me
in the middle of the night

00:08:00.749 --> 00:08:04.043
I'mma run your ass aground.
I'd run 'em aground and stop

00:08:04.654 --> 00:08:06.453
and say [yells] "Y'all all right?"

00:08:06.520 --> 00:08:08.253
They go yeah we're okay a**hole.

00:08:08.320 --> 00:08:11.438
-No way. No way.
-Yeah. I've done that a couple times.

00:08:12.510 --> 00:08:16.373
Red mangroves they call that
the walking tree because of the roots.

00:08:16.440 --> 00:08:18.813
See how the roots
kind of come out and walk out?

00:08:18.880 --> 00:08:20.498
-Yeah.
-Call it the walking tree.

00:08:20.565 --> 00:08:24.179
I call it an island builder
because if one of those little pods

00:08:24.660 --> 00:08:29.083
float along and jump on an oyster bar
and stick up on an oyster bar

00:08:29.150 --> 00:08:31.212
and it grows the roots, drops the leaves,

00:08:31.279 --> 00:08:32.886
another one grows another one

00:08:33.477 --> 00:08:36.163
50 years,
you got all them leaves you got an island.

00:08:36.230 --> 00:08:37.550
-It attracts everything?
-Yeah.

00:08:37.617 --> 00:08:40.846
It's some of the most amazing nature.
I gotta say.

00:08:40.913 --> 00:08:44.123
-All of this leads up into
where I take you buggy riding at.

00:08:44.190 --> 00:08:46.715
-We're gonna go up there?
-We're gonna go up there.

00:08:46.782 --> 00:08:50.163
Rivers from here
go all the way up to there.

00:08:50.230 --> 00:08:51.230
[country music]

00:09:04.865 --> 00:09:08.634
[Steve] My great granddaddy,
my momma, which I call her momma.

00:09:08.701 --> 00:09:10.194
She was really my grandma.

00:09:10.261 --> 00:09:12.754
My father died when I was real young.

00:09:12.821 --> 00:09:15.590
My grandmother and grandfather adopted me.

00:09:16.090 --> 00:09:18.859
So when I say my momma I mean my grandma

00:09:18.926 --> 00:09:20.495
but she actually was my mother.

00:09:20.562 --> 00:09:23.842
-They all lived out here?
-Right here. This is where she was born.

00:09:23.909 --> 00:09:24.981
1900.

00:09:25.048 --> 00:09:26.349
-Were they the only ones?

00:09:26.416 --> 00:09:28.601
No.
There was a couple other families.

00:09:28.668 --> 00:09:30.083
The Johnsons were out here.

00:09:30.150 --> 00:09:33.283
-It's a big island.
-The same one built off the Calusa Shells?

00:09:33.363 --> 00:09:34.838
Built off the Calusa Shells.

00:09:34.905 --> 00:09:39.873
And then the thousands of years
of the leaves and stuff drop and composite.

00:09:39.940 --> 00:09:41.841
My grandfather, great grandfather,

00:09:42.426 --> 00:09:46.333
he farmed islands all around here.

00:09:46.805 --> 00:09:49.192
And then Watson, who killed people,

00:09:49.259 --> 00:09:52.082
he had a 40-acre sugar cane factory.

00:09:52.149 --> 00:09:54.561
He was a murderer. He killed Belle Starr.

00:09:55.554 --> 00:09:57.634
Yeah this was a bad area.

00:09:58.390 --> 00:10:01.737
You asked me earlier
why would people move down here?

00:10:02.210 --> 00:10:05.843
They get away after
the turn of the Civil War.

00:10:05.910 --> 00:10:07.940
They didn't like the Northern Rule.

00:10:08.007 --> 00:10:11.258
Hit that middle post up there Pete
when I get you up to it.

00:10:11.325 --> 00:10:13.425
-They just wanted to be free?

00:10:13.492 --> 00:10:16.983
They didn't want to have
Northern judges telling them what to do.

00:10:17.050 --> 00:10:20.117
-So this is really
the final frontier in the country right?

00:10:20.184 --> 00:10:21.949
-Well we call it that a lot.

00:10:22.016 --> 00:10:24.690
-California Gold Rush, 1849.

00:10:24.757 --> 00:10:29.295
This place in 1849,
just a handful of people right?

00:10:29.362 --> 00:10:31.644
There was people
stretched out on the islands.

00:10:31.711 --> 00:10:35.417
Now these Calusa Indian Mounds
I may be off just a little bit.

00:10:36.170 --> 00:10:40.313
There was 47 of them
throughout from Marco to the Keys.

00:10:40.380 --> 00:10:43.083
And people was inhabited on a lot of them.

00:10:43.650 --> 00:10:44.569
Excuse me.

00:10:44.636 --> 00:10:47.940
They inhabited a lot of them
because they were great farming lands.

00:10:48.007 --> 00:10:50.516
My great-grandfather farmed a lot of it.

00:10:50.583 --> 00:10:53.003
Matter of fact
he got along good with Watson.

00:10:53.070 --> 00:10:55.482
He was part of the crowd that killed him.

00:10:56.165 --> 00:10:57.165
Him and my uncle.

00:10:58.485 --> 00:11:00.494
Well look this is Sand Fly Island.

00:11:01.010 --> 00:11:04.997
At one time there wasn't as many trees
on this place. It was really empty.

00:11:05.064 --> 00:11:06.888
This is a map of the island.

00:11:07.360 --> 00:11:09.418
This shows the Calusa Indians.

00:11:09.840 --> 00:11:11.853
And this is a picture

00:11:11.920 --> 00:11:14.852
of my family's homestead
when they lived here on the island.

00:11:14.919 --> 00:11:15.849
It's a big house.

00:11:15.916 --> 00:11:18.363
It's the second largest home
in the islands.

00:11:18.430 --> 00:11:19.796
Watson had the first.

00:11:20.870 --> 00:11:23.951
-Okay brief history on Watson.
Who's this guy Watson?

00:11:24.018 --> 00:11:27.229
Watson was a man that come…
Old gunfighter from out West.

00:11:27.296 --> 00:11:28.197
Okay.

00:11:28.264 --> 00:11:31.103
So he moved down here
and he started sugar cane.

00:11:31.170 --> 00:11:35.660
And they say that he would kill
some of his helpers instead of paying them.

00:11:35.727 --> 00:11:36.759
Shot a lady.

00:11:36.826 --> 00:11:41.159
And then other people settled
on some of the islands that he used.

00:11:41.510 --> 00:11:43.383
And he didn't want them on there.

00:11:43.450 --> 00:11:46.226
And they found one woman.
She was pregnant, gutted.

00:11:46.680 --> 00:11:48.337
Floated up on an oyster bar.

00:11:48.404 --> 00:11:51.110
So the locals said we can't have this.

00:11:51.540 --> 00:11:53.726
They were scared of him. He was a bad man.

00:11:54.403 --> 00:11:57.389
So he was one of the only people

00:11:57.456 --> 00:12:00.063
that had a boat with a motor in it.

00:12:00.130 --> 00:12:03.031
Back then, pop pop pop.
That's what the boat sounded…

00:12:03.110 --> 00:12:05.794
They could hear it coming
from all because listen,

00:12:06.252 --> 00:12:08.803
there ain't no generators or nothing.

00:12:08.870 --> 00:12:10.501
They could hear the boat coming,

00:12:10.568 --> 00:12:13.033
so the townsfolk
got together on Chokoloskee.

00:12:13.100 --> 00:12:15.505
And they said listen, you're under arrest.

00:12:15.980 --> 00:12:20.278
And he said you ain't gonna arrest me
and he pulled up a double barrel shotgun,

00:12:20.345 --> 00:12:22.843
and back then they had the paper shells,

00:12:22.910 --> 00:12:25.501
and it went bloop instead of going bam.

00:12:25.898 --> 00:12:27.192
And when it went bloop,

00:12:27.818 --> 00:12:30.083
several people fired and killed him.

00:12:30.583 --> 00:12:32.618
My cousin still got one of the guns.

00:12:32.685 --> 00:12:34.201
Here's the concrete post.

00:12:34.780 --> 00:12:36.730
Some of them where the house was at.

00:12:36.797 --> 00:12:38.621
-Right.
-And look to your right.

00:12:39.690 --> 00:12:42.337
-There's the cistern they drank out of.
-Okay.

00:12:42.415 --> 00:12:44.283
Now if you look on this sign,

00:12:45.576 --> 00:12:48.234
there's my granddaddy's name,
Charlie Boggess.

00:12:48.301 --> 00:12:51.533
-Oh that's so cool.
-His family were among those pioneers.

00:12:52.033 --> 00:12:54.859
My mama was born here in 1900.

00:12:55.380 --> 00:12:59.563
Said when she was a kid
growing up here they dug a well.

00:12:59.630 --> 00:13:02.540
It's called an artisan well
which means it's free flowing.

00:13:02.607 --> 00:13:04.617
There's conc blocks from the house.

00:13:05.140 --> 00:13:08.166
That this well
would be seven, eight feet, in the air.

00:13:08.233 --> 00:13:11.183
They played in it as a kid.
This were some of the water.

00:13:11.250 --> 00:13:12.443
You can drink it.

00:13:12.510 --> 00:13:14.769
-So that's nice fresh water.
-It's well water.

00:13:14.836 --> 00:13:16.779
But it's fresh. It's not salty at all.

00:13:16.846 --> 00:13:18.757
-It's a little teeny salty.

00:13:19.370 --> 00:13:22.003
But mama said she used to play in it.

00:13:22.070 --> 00:13:25.548
You know when they were kids
it was shooting up six seven foot.

00:13:25.615 --> 00:13:27.763
And kids you can imagine.

00:13:27.830 --> 00:13:30.531
Probably three four families
lived on this island.

00:13:31.031 --> 00:13:35.207
And all the kids would get together
in the summer and play in the water.

00:13:35.760 --> 00:13:38.693
Be careful Pete
'cause I imagine this is slippery.

00:13:38.760 --> 00:13:41.073
It's been a long time since I walked it.

00:13:41.140 --> 00:13:43.813
This is the red mangrove
I was telling you about.

00:13:43.880 --> 00:13:45.428
-The walking tree.
-Right.

00:13:45.495 --> 00:13:49.023
You can see the roots are walking
and see all the leaves dropping?

00:13:49.090 --> 00:13:50.019
-Yep.

00:13:50.086 --> 00:13:53.766
-Another thousand years from now
it'll be knee high it'll be hard ground.

00:13:53.833 --> 00:13:56.045
And plus it's like compost. It grows.

00:13:56.545 --> 00:13:59.824
It'll be good area to grow in.
They clear these trees out.

00:14:00.520 --> 00:14:03.875
Used to, they would take the black mangrove

00:14:04.565 --> 00:14:07.323
tree and cut it and burn it for coal.

00:14:07.990 --> 00:14:11.326
It would go to Key West
and that's what they run in the steamers.

00:14:11.940 --> 00:14:14.443
Used it for fires. Used it for heating.

00:14:14.510 --> 00:14:16.721
-So Steve
you know your history pretty well.

00:14:16.788 --> 00:14:19.421
Well I love history.
That's… you know, I love it.

00:14:19.488 --> 00:14:21.510
I love my family's background.

00:14:21.577 --> 00:14:24.365
My fourth, fifth, great-grandfather

00:14:25.226 --> 00:14:28.857
fought in
the Spanish-American War, the Civil War.

00:14:28.930 --> 00:14:31.360
He fought for the United States of America.

00:14:31.930 --> 00:14:34.202
He was a commissioner.
He was a mailman.

00:14:34.710 --> 00:14:37.957
He wrote a book called
A Veteran of Four Wars.

00:14:38.024 --> 00:14:41.508
His name F.C.M. Boggess.

00:14:42.040 --> 00:14:44.636
B-O-G-G-E-S-S is his name.

00:14:45.320 --> 00:14:47.582
That's my family from Fort Ogden.

00:14:47.649 --> 00:14:48.933
And they're still there.

00:14:49.000 --> 00:14:50.529
Got roads named after him.

00:14:51.041 --> 00:14:53.713
-So you are old Florida, Steve.

00:14:53.780 --> 00:14:55.589
My family is old Florida.

00:14:56.540 --> 00:14:57.952
-About as old as it gets.

00:14:58.840 --> 00:15:00.428
Here before it was a state.

00:15:01.170 --> 00:15:03.475
-Before it was a state.
-Before it was a state.

00:15:03.542 --> 00:15:07.707
So the Calusas weren't here
by the time the settlers got here right?

00:15:08.734 --> 00:15:12.511
-They were long gone.
-I heard that the last Calusa died…

00:15:13.590 --> 00:15:14.539
in Cuba.

00:15:14.990 --> 00:15:15.901
Okay.

00:15:15.968 --> 00:15:17.189
That they went to Cuba.

00:15:18.450 --> 00:15:19.883
-Who's this?
-Yeah Darryl.

00:15:20.315 --> 00:15:21.373
-He did what?

00:15:21.440 --> 00:15:24.503
I don't know if he wants the people
to know but he started it.

00:15:24.570 --> 00:15:26.805
He was the biggest smuggler there was.

00:15:27.430 --> 00:15:29.961
-Marijuana smuggler.
-[Darryl] Oh we're going home.

00:15:30.028 --> 00:15:32.467
Hey Darryl. Say hi to Peter.

00:15:32.534 --> 00:15:34.718
Are you working all day today?

00:15:34.785 --> 00:15:36.646
-I'll be home.
-You'll be home?

00:15:36.713 --> 00:15:38.388
-Can we come by and see ya?
-Sure.

00:15:38.455 --> 00:15:39.383
Okay.

00:15:39.450 --> 00:15:41.243
This guy here I've almost raised.

00:15:41.310 --> 00:15:43.298
-He did.
-That's what he was saying.

00:15:43.365 --> 00:15:45.611
-Stayed at my house more than his.
-Yeah.

00:15:45.678 --> 00:15:47.646
[Peter] So we're gonna go to his house?

00:15:47.713 --> 00:15:49.883
-If you want to.
-Yeah. That would be great.

00:15:49.950 --> 00:15:51.211
Now he does boat tours.

00:15:51.278 --> 00:15:53.219
Yeah. He's helping out his nephew.

00:15:53.943 --> 00:15:54.943
That's all.

00:15:56.656 --> 00:15:57.715
[water flowing]

00:16:03.365 --> 00:16:05.763
We're gonna go to the Rod and Gun Club.

00:16:05.830 --> 00:16:07.965
We're gonna go to Everglades City.

00:16:08.032 --> 00:16:09.788
We're gonna go through the channel.

00:16:09.868 --> 00:16:13.040
We've done some
marijuana smuggling up into Everglades City

00:16:13.107 --> 00:16:16.730
but you got to understand
I'm gonna make a lot of people mad.

00:16:16.797 --> 00:16:20.490
Everglades City,
back then the people there,

00:16:21.468 --> 00:16:23.818
they didn't compare to us on Chokoloskee.

00:16:23.885 --> 00:16:26.761
We were the ones that knew the way around.

00:16:26.828 --> 00:16:29.789
We were the ones
that knew how to get there.

00:16:29.856 --> 00:16:33.986
-So there are basically two towns here,
Chokoloskee, Everglades City?

00:16:34.534 --> 00:16:36.466
-And there's a rival?
-There's a rival.

00:16:36.533 --> 00:16:39.598
There used to be a rival.
They used to not get along.

00:16:39.665 --> 00:16:42.432
-And now we're gonna Everglades City.

00:16:43.551 --> 00:16:47.445
-So Steve, you had
your good hears from '81 to '87.

00:16:47.512 --> 00:16:49.078
'85 I was in prison.

00:16:49.145 --> 00:16:51.245
The first time I did five years.

00:16:51.833 --> 00:16:54.173
Then the second time I was out

00:16:55.105 --> 00:16:59.859
in my sons truck,
it had a hunting rifle underneath the seat.

00:17:00.287 --> 00:17:03.327
I had my door open
and a deputy walked by and seen it.

00:17:03.907 --> 00:17:05.980
Said, "You ain't supposed to have a gun."

00:17:06.047 --> 00:17:09.660
Arrested me for
felon in possession of a firearm.

00:17:11.380 --> 00:17:14.607
I said I'm just hunting. I'm not…
"Well you can't have it."

00:17:15.499 --> 00:17:17.768
I did five years in state prison for that.

00:17:17.835 --> 00:17:20.332
-So you went to
federal prison the first time?

00:17:20.399 --> 00:17:22.502
-Like a boy scout camp.
-Boy scout camp?

00:17:22.569 --> 00:17:24.012
-Boy scout camp.
-Easy?

00:17:24.447 --> 00:17:25.727
Eglin Air Force Base.

00:17:26.384 --> 00:17:28.395
-Okay, and then how was state prison?

00:17:28.857 --> 00:17:31.176
If I woulda went to
state prison the first time

00:17:31.243 --> 00:17:33.694
I wouldn't have never went to jail again

00:17:33.761 --> 00:17:35.114
'cause it was horrible.

00:17:36.321 --> 00:17:38.967
-Wadn't no fun.
-Were you up in Raiford?

00:17:39.034 --> 00:17:42.471
I've been all over but I don't think
I ever made it to Raiford.

00:17:43.288 --> 00:17:47.127
But I was all over all different prisons.

00:17:47.194 --> 00:17:48.900
-That was hardcore?
-Horrible.

00:17:49.398 --> 00:17:50.762
Things you can't imagine.

00:17:50.829 --> 00:17:54.410
Just dream about prison
in the movies and that's what it was.

00:17:54.946 --> 00:17:57.459
When I got out, yes sir,

00:17:57.927 --> 00:18:00.141
no sir, I don't speed.

00:18:00.537 --> 00:18:03.977
When I get in my truck
and start it before I put it in gear,

00:18:05.377 --> 00:18:06.830
I don't break the law.

00:18:06.897 --> 00:18:08.544
That put me straight.

00:18:08.611 --> 00:18:11.029
-So all your money gone
after that point in time?

00:18:11.096 --> 00:18:13.178
By the time I got out, yeah, it was gone.

00:18:13.246 --> 00:18:16.137
You know the bad part of it all,

00:18:16.780 --> 00:18:19.372
is I missed that much time with my kids.

00:18:19.439 --> 00:18:20.968
-Yeah.
-That's what it was.

00:18:21.609 --> 00:18:23.257
I look on it now though…

00:18:24.667 --> 00:18:28.915
I've got a 20 year old daughter
I raised from a newborn.

00:18:29.395 --> 00:18:32.773
If I wouldn't have did all that
I would have never got her.

00:18:32.840 --> 00:18:34.504
So I look at it like

00:18:34.978 --> 00:18:37.019
it was horrible but in the end

00:18:37.412 --> 00:18:39.552
I wouldn't have had my daughter

00:18:39.994 --> 00:18:44.071
if I wouldn't have went through all that
'cause I would have never met her mother.

00:18:44.138 --> 00:18:47.276
-Right. Life does its weird thing
you could never set up.

00:18:47.343 --> 00:18:51.731
So God paid me with having a little girl
and I raised her from a newborn.

00:18:52.251 --> 00:18:54.216
Her mother had some problems

00:18:54.283 --> 00:18:57.505
and they said that
she couldn't be around Stevie

00:18:57.572 --> 00:19:00.792
but we made time
for her mother to see her.

00:19:01.340 --> 00:19:04.202
Her mother drowned in a swimming pool.

00:19:04.269 --> 00:19:06.368
She had a few beer,

00:19:06.869 --> 00:19:10.385
and got in a swimming pool swimming
you know nice and warm

00:19:10.769 --> 00:19:11.905
and fell asleep.

00:19:11.972 --> 00:19:14.312
-Oh man. Jeez.
-And drownded.

00:19:17.730 --> 00:19:20.220
-Everglades City?
-Everglades City.

00:19:20.647 --> 00:19:23.181
Home of the rich people.

00:19:23.248 --> 00:19:24.893
-Mostly second homes now?

00:19:24.960 --> 00:19:25.862
-Most of them.

00:19:25.929 --> 00:19:27.439
-So Chokoloskee different?

00:19:27.506 --> 00:19:30.384
Totally different people.
Like I said there was a time

00:19:30.451 --> 00:19:33.756
to where Everglades people
and Chokoloskee people didn't get along.

00:19:33.823 --> 00:19:34.945
Now you guys are good?

00:19:35.012 --> 00:19:36.446
Yeah most of the time.

00:19:37.089 --> 00:19:39.572
They still some of them's
a little snooty actin'.

00:19:39.639 --> 00:19:40.805
They're stone crabbers.

00:19:40.872 --> 00:19:43.436
Stone crabbers back then
they made good money.

00:19:43.503 --> 00:19:46.630
We were old mullet fishermen,
we pulled nets. We were…

00:19:47.556 --> 00:19:49.483
Fishy smelly all the time

00:19:50.156 --> 00:19:52.390
and had old boats with motors on it.

00:19:52.457 --> 00:19:56.133
They had big crab boats
and they were fancy.

00:19:56.600 --> 00:20:00.352
Now I got some good friends that are
from Everglades City we got along with.

00:20:00.419 --> 00:20:02.113
That's where one of them lives.

00:20:02.180 --> 00:20:04.721
-That smaller home?
-No the big yellow one.

00:20:04.788 --> 00:20:06.877
-Oh that one okay.
-Yeah good man.

00:20:07.316 --> 00:20:08.592
-Look at the homes.
-Yeah.

00:20:08.659 --> 00:20:09.846
They ain't cheap.

00:20:09.913 --> 00:20:13.259
That city dock,
my grandfather pulled alongside of

00:20:13.326 --> 00:20:16.776
and unloaded a boat
of Cuban rum into his car.

00:20:17.310 --> 00:20:20.904
When he ran around a corner
a constable jumped out onto…

00:20:20.971 --> 00:20:24.865
You know old '30s with the running boards
down the side of the cars.

00:20:25.286 --> 00:20:28.306
When he jumped on it they shot him off
with shotgun.

00:20:28.373 --> 00:20:30.222
-Right up here?
-Right there.

00:20:30.289 --> 00:20:33.523
See the city was built
all the way down here. Had a streetcar.

00:20:33.590 --> 00:20:36.280
This road was houses
and buildings and shops.

00:20:36.347 --> 00:20:38.320
We had a…
This was the county seat.

00:20:38.387 --> 00:20:40.043
That's where everything happened.

00:20:40.110 --> 00:20:43.475
They had a movie theater,
and a garage, and everything.

00:20:44.039 --> 00:20:46.044
-And what what happened? A hurricane?

00:20:46.111 --> 00:20:48.448
Yeah in 1960, Hurricane Donna.

00:20:48.515 --> 00:20:51.586
And after that they moved
everything to Naples

00:20:51.653 --> 00:20:53.825
because you know Everglades was small.

00:20:54.490 --> 00:20:57.651
Now we're coming up on
the Rod and Gun Club.

00:20:57.718 --> 00:21:00.228
It's been here since the Civil War.

00:21:00.988 --> 00:21:02.181
-That building?
-Yep.

00:21:02.248 --> 00:21:04.175
Still looks just like it inside.

00:21:04.242 --> 00:21:06.897
Now Peter,
if you look over here on your left

00:21:06.964 --> 00:21:11.058
that's where my family when they moved in
from a Sand Fly Island we was just at.

00:21:11.125 --> 00:21:12.393
This is where they lived.

00:21:12.460 --> 00:21:14.978
-They came in from the island?
-And come into here.

00:21:15.045 --> 00:21:17.141
Now this whole island was clean clear.

00:21:17.208 --> 00:21:20.241
There was like
four or five homes on it, all family.

00:21:20.308 --> 00:21:22.913
The house burnt down and they moved here.

00:21:22.980 --> 00:21:26.009
You had to park over here
and go across to the boat.

00:21:26.076 --> 00:21:27.553
No way to get to it.

00:21:27.620 --> 00:21:30.429
So this is where all my Thanksgivings

00:21:30.496 --> 00:21:32.904
and Sunday dinners after church

00:21:32.971 --> 00:21:34.658
this is where we had it.

00:21:34.725 --> 00:21:36.863
-So this town was thriving back then?

00:21:36.930 --> 00:21:39.033
-Thriving up until Hurricane Donna.

00:21:39.100 --> 00:21:40.836
-Okay Rod and Gun Club.

00:21:40.903 --> 00:21:43.524
It's a restaurant,
motel, they got some rooms.

00:21:43.591 --> 00:21:47.230
They don't use the rooms upstairs
but I think they're redoing them.

00:21:47.297 --> 00:21:51.382
Hey this was in the movie Gone Fishing
with Danny Glover and Joe Pesci.

00:21:53.250 --> 00:21:54.983
[Steve] No, around the cleat.

00:21:55.050 --> 00:21:56.483
[Peter] Now you're a cameraman.

00:21:58.090 --> 00:22:00.751
-Oh you know how to tie a boat up.
-Yeah.

00:22:01.449 --> 00:22:05.194
I worked on Lake Tahoe one summer
as the boat dude.

00:22:06.120 --> 00:22:08.646
I've actually seen it.
I went in here years ago.

00:22:08.713 --> 00:22:10.992
-Did you film it?
-A very tiny bit of it.

00:22:12.110 --> 00:22:14.036
[Peter] This is the cultural gem.

00:22:14.103 --> 00:22:16.835
Oh yeah. It is old world

00:22:17.360 --> 00:22:19.463
lacquered up old Florida.

00:22:20.000 --> 00:22:21.643
[Steve] Is this not beautiful?

00:22:21.710 --> 00:22:22.764
This is unbelievable.

00:22:22.831 --> 00:22:24.973
Cash register. They only take cash.

00:22:25.040 --> 00:22:27.401
-Walk back here and look.
Look at the fireplace.

00:22:27.468 --> 00:22:28.383
-Yep.

00:22:28.450 --> 00:22:30.831
-Had presidents and royalty come here.

00:22:32.680 --> 00:22:34.643
-Right. Didn't Roosevelt come here?

00:22:34.710 --> 00:22:35.769
Yeah, I believe so.

00:22:36.257 --> 00:22:37.553
Look at this bar.

00:22:37.620 --> 00:22:40.133
It's dark
so the camera's not picking up everything

00:22:40.200 --> 00:22:42.778
but you got the pirate theme here.

00:22:42.845 --> 00:22:44.976
You didn't really have pirates out here?

00:22:45.043 --> 00:22:48.107
-Well yeah there was Pirate Gomez.
That was with Blackbeard.

00:22:48.174 --> 00:22:50.773
-He came this far?
-He come on the islands yeah.

00:22:50.840 --> 00:22:52.725
He buried treasure

00:22:53.287 --> 00:22:56.137
on my family's land

00:22:56.731 --> 00:22:58.466
in Fort Ogden.

00:22:58.533 --> 00:23:00.846
You can watch it with Josh Gates.

00:23:01.350 --> 00:23:04.387
He goes all over the world doing stuff,

00:23:04.915 --> 00:23:06.263
finding treasures.

00:23:06.330 --> 00:23:07.709
And he was hunting

00:23:08.532 --> 00:23:10.697
for the treasure from Pirate

00:23:11.647 --> 00:23:16.316
Gomez asked my family, Miss Lady Boggess

00:23:16.784 --> 00:23:19.452
if he could put it there
on her property in Fort Ogden

00:23:19.519 --> 00:23:21.408
where the Peace River run up.

00:23:21.475 --> 00:23:23.628
Sure did. You can see it on TV. Watch it.

00:23:24.560 --> 00:23:27.327
Josh Gates has got it on there.
Expedition Unknown.

